{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"alias":"busy-taboo-tag","description":"## Why\nThe plan-review gate shipped advisory-by-default with uniform thresholds\n(block_threshold=0.95, default_posture=advisory for all 32 criteria) so it could\nnot block during calibration. We have now dogfooded enough to calibrate per-criterion\ndefaults from real data: 167 REVIEW_RESULT sidecars / 106 tickets / 1,329 findings.\n\n## What\nDerive per-criterion (default_posture, block_threshold) defaults from the dogfooded\nREVIEW_RESULT corpus, using two reliability signals:\n- Verifier-refutation (dense form): per-criterion `validity` distribution, P(dropped),\n  P(indeterminate), and the per-binary-subquestion \"no\" profile. (The literal `dropped`\n  outcome alone is too sparse — 18 total — so use continuous validity.)\n- Voluntary revision-response: a material_fingerprint change between consecutive reviews\n  of a ticket = a genuine revision. Exact finding-id survival is CONFOUNDED by finder\n  text-churn (~100% false \"resolution\" for LLM criteria vs 13% for the one deterministic\n  criterion P6), so attribute revisions at criterion-load-delta granularity, not exact id.\n- Fire-rate denominator from coverage.routing (which criteria ran per review).\n\n## Scope\n1. Sidecar enrichment (APPROVED, must stay UX-invisible to library/MCP/CLI): persist\n   fields that make the revision signal cleanly measurable going forward (normalized\n   finding id + location), without changing the surfaced verdict shape.\n2. Offline calibration analysis over the sidecars -> per-criterion reliability profile +\n   proposed (posture, threshold).\n3. Step 5 = INTERACTIVE review with the user for borderline / low-sample criteria\n   (block vs advisory) — some may be clear blockers despite small n.\n4. Apply agreed thresholds to src/rebar/llm/plan_review/criteria_routing.json\n   (block_threshold + default_posture per criterion; registry reads it directly).\n5. Step 7 validation: run plan-review with the new thresholds on 20 randomly-sampled\n   tickets that historically had high finding counts or overlay triggers. If any BLOCK,\n   discuss with the user; otherwise the plan is approved.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Sidecar enrichment lands with a test proving the surfaced verdict (library/MCP/CLI\n      return shapes) is byte-unchanged — enrichment is observability-only.\n- [ ] A reproducible offline calibration script reads the sidecars and emits a\n      per-criterion table: n, mean validity, P(dropped), P(indeterminate), revision-response\n      (criterion-load-delta), fire-rate, and a proposed (posture, threshold).\n- [ ] Step 5 interactive decision is recorded (which criteria flip to blocking and at what\n      threshold, which stay advisory, and the rationale per criterion).\n- [ ] criteria_routing.json updated to the agreed per-criterion defaults; lint + the\n      plan-review unit tests pass.\n- [ ] Step 7: 20 sampled tickets re-reviewed under the new thresholds; the block outcomes\n      are reported. Zero unexpected blocks => approved; any block => discussed.","id":"3d3d-da49-c3f3-4298","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"Calibrate plan-review per-criterion block thresholds from dogfooded REVIEW_RESULT data"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1782689544425217001,"uuid":"a3c1ac24-4570-46c4-994b-0c2cdb0cca40"}